{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17565658","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17565658"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T23:30:42+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T23:30:42+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18278"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18278","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18278"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.02,0.04,0.15,0.78]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10992"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105628"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10992","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10992"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18278"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88071"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"26"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"318"},{"type":"tags","id":"1575"},{"type":"tags","id":"1674"},{"type":"tags","id":"2706"},{"type":"tags","id":"3768"},{"type":"tags","id":"4607"},{"type":"tags","id":"5587"},{"type":"tags","id":"9218"},{"type":"tags","id":"12917"},{"type":"tags","id":"12921"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25535"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39715"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105628","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/105628"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe surgical intern is asked to review a 72-year-old woman on the ward following a right hemicolectomy performed 24 hours ago. The nurse reports her blood pressure has dropped over the past hour. She has a medical history of hypertension, osteoarthritis, and chronic kidney disease stage II. Her regular medications are amlodipine and paracetamol.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears unwell and anxious. Her pulse rate is 115/min, blood pressure 85/50 mmHg, respiratory rate 22/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.5\u00b0C. Her peripheries are cold and clammy. Her surgical wound dressing is newly dressed, with some haemoserous strikethrough. Her abdomen is soft but tender around the wound site. Her jugular venous pressure is not elevated. Heart sounds are normal with no murmurs. Her chest is clear on auscultation. Her urine output over the past four hours is 15 mL. Recent blood results show:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHaemoglobin 92 g/L (115-165)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhite cell count 12.5 x10\u003Csup\u003E9\u003C/sup\u003E /L (4.0-11.0)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESodium 138 mmol/L (135-145)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPotassium 4.2 mmol/L (3.5-5.0)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUrea 12.2 mmol/L (3.0-8.0)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECreatinine 156 \u00b5mol/L (45-90)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELactate 4.2 mmol/L (0.5-2.2)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely type of shock in this patient?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Cardiogenic shock","Neurogenic shock","Obstructive shock","Septic shock","Hypovolaemic shock"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with clinical features consistent with shock: hypotension, tachycardia, cold peripheries, reduced urine output, and elevated lactate. The pattern of findings most strongly suggests \u003Cstrong\u003Ehypovolaemic shock\u003C/strong\u003E, likely multifactorial. The drop in haemoglobin might be secondary to surgical blood loss, and given her recent surgery she likely has minimal to no oral intake. The deteriorating renal function (elevated urea and creatinine from baseline CKD) further supports reduced renal perfusion due to hypovolaemia. The absence of fever or significant inflammatory response makes other causes less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECardiogenic shock\u003C/strong\u003E would typically present with features of heart failure including elevated jugular venous pressure, pulmonary oedema, and a history of cardiac disease. These features are absent in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENeurogenic shock\u003C/strong\u003E typically occurs after spinal cord injury and presents with bradycardia and warm peripheries due to loss of sympathetic tone. This patient\u0027s tachycardia and cold peripheries make this diagnosis unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESeptic shock\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with warm peripheries, fever, and a more marked inflammatory response. While the white cell count is mildly elevated, the absence of fever and the cold peripheries make this less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EObstructive shock\u003C/strong\u003E (as seen in cardiac tamponade or pulmonary embolism) would typically present with elevated jugular venous pressure and specific features related to the underlying cause. The examination findings do not support this diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe key to differentiating between types of shock lies in careful clinical assessment of volume status, cardiac function, and peripheral perfusion. In this case, the recent surgery, drop in haemoglobin, and cold peripheries point strongly towards hypovolaemia as the cause. \u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Early recognition of shock type through clinical assessment guides immediate management and improves outcomes","Hypovolaemic shock presents with tachycardia, hypotension, cold peripheries, and reduced urine output","History and examination findings help differentiate between cardiogenic, distributive, hypovolaemic and obstructive shock"],"references":["Haseer Koya H, Paul M. Shock. [Updated 2023 Jul 24]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK531492/","Holmes CL, Walley KR. The evaluation and management of shock. Clin Chest Med. 2003 Dec;24(4):775\u2013789. doi: 10.1016/s0272-5231(03)00107-2. Available at: https://doi.org/10.1016/s0272-5231(03)00107-2"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88071"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18278"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88071","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/88071"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-11T09:30:59+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-02T00:05:23+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10992"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105628"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"26","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/26"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd7c","name":"Critical Care Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":n